-- SAIC Motor Leads China Car Shares Higher on Demand Outlook
-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 2010-10-12T04:33:06Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-12/saic-motor-advances-most-since-may-2009-after-earnings-nine-month-forecast.html
SAIC Motor Corp.  led China auto
stocks higher in Shanghai trading after saying profit may have
jumped more than 140 percent in the first nine months on an
increase in car sales.  SAIC Motor  climbed 7.4 percent to 18.50 yuan as of the
11:30 a.m. trading break on the Shanghai Securities Exchange
after earlier today climbing as much as 10 percent to 18.95 yuan,
the highest intraday level since Jan. 7. Net income may have
surged from 3.97 billion yuan ($595 million) a year earlier
after vehicle sales increased more than 36 percent, the Chinese
automaker said in a statement today. The benchmark Shanghai
Composite Index declined 0.3 percent.  Chinese carmaker stocks also rallied in Hong Kong on
speculation the outlook for sales has improved.  Brilliance China
Automotive Holdings Ltd.  gained as much as 10 percent to HK$6.00
and  Guangzhou Automobile Group Co.  advanced for the first time
in seven sessions. Hong Kong’s benchmark Hang Seng Index slipped
0.5 percent.  Investors are buying in anticipation of improving car sales
numbers for September which will be released today, said  Leah Jiang , an analyst at Macquarie Group Ltd. in Shanghai.  “September is normally a higher season for auto sales and
the feedback from dealers has been quite positive,” Jiang said.
“They’re getting more visitor traffic and there is a pickup in
buying from the past several months.”  The China Association of Automobile Manufacturers is due to
release September vehicle wholesale delivery data at 3.30 p.m.
in Beijing.  Auto sales in China may reach 17 million units this year,
up 25 percent from a year earlier, Xinhua News reported
yesterday, citing the manufacturers’ association.  -- Liza Lin . Editors:  Suresh Seshadri ,  Jonathan Annells   To contact Bloomberg News staff on this story:
